<div id="overviewBlock">
	<h3>Overview:</h3>
	<p>France's colonial territories were of very high importance after the embarrassment of occupation during World War II. Algeria, in particular, was a complicated case because it involved large numbers of French settlers, the <em>pieds-noirs</em>. Despite international support for Algerian independence, right-wing factions in the military and among the colonizers remained committed to staying the course. After Charles de Gaulle presided over French withdrawal, the cause of the <em>pieds-noirs</em> has remained divisive in French political life, particularly on the right.</p>
</div>
<div id="readingBlock">
	<h3>Reading assignment:</h3>
	<p>Sowerwine, Charles. <em>France since 1870: Culture, Politics and Society</em>, pp. 226-306.</p>
</div>
